## Backend Architecture (apps/api)

The Symfony backend is responsible for all business logic, persistence, and auth. The frontend is treated as just another API consumer.

{% if use_ddd %}
### Domain-Driven Design Layers

The backend is structured around DDD layers. Each layer has a strict dependency direction: Domain has no outward dependencies; Application depends only on Domain; Infrastructure depends on Application and Domain.

```
src/
├── Domain/               # Pure business logic - no framework dependencies
│   ├── Model/            # Entities, value objects, aggregates
│   ├── Service/          # Domain services (stateless business rules)
│   ├── Event/            # Domain events
│   └── Repository/       # Repository interfaces (contracts)
├── Application/          # Use cases / application services
│   ├── Command/          # Write-side: commands and handlers (CQRS)
│   ├── Query/            # Read-side: queries and handlers (CQRS)
│   └── DTO/              # Data Transfer Objects for use case boundaries
├── Infrastructure/       # Framework and external adapters
│   ├── Persistence/      # Doctrine entity mappings, repository implementations
│   ├── Http/             # Symfony controllers (thin - delegate to Application layer)
│   └── Messaging/        # Symfony Messenger handlers and transports
└── Shared/               # Cross-cutting: exceptions, interfaces, helpers
```

**Bounded Contexts:** Each major feature area is its own subdirectory under each layer (e.g. `Domain/Model/User/`, `Domain/Model/Order/`). A context owns its entities, services, and repository contracts.

{% else %}
### Layered Architecture

```
src/
├── Controller/           # Symfony controllers - thin HTTP layer only
├── Entity/               # Doctrine ORM entities
├── Repository/           # Doctrine repositories with query methods
├── Service/              # Business logic services
├── DTO/                  # Request/response Data Transfer Objects
├── EventListener/        # Symfony event listeners and subscribers
└── Exception/            # Domain-specific exceptions
```

**Controllers are thin.** They validate the HTTP request, call a Service, and return a response. Business logic lives in Services, not Controllers.
{% endif %}

