{% if use_auth %}
## Authentication Flow

{% if auth_method == "jwt" %}
### JWT Authentication (end-to-end)

```
1. User submits login form (apps/web)
   └── POST /api/auth/login  { email, password }

2. Symfony validates credentials
   └── Returns { token, refresh_token, user }

3. Next.js stores tokens
   ├── access_token: httpOnly cookie (set by Next.js API route)
   └── refresh_token: httpOnly cookie

4. Subsequent requests
   └── Next.js lib/api.ts reads the cookie and attaches
       Authorization: Bearer <token>

5. Token refresh (transparent)
   └── If the API returns 401, lib/api.ts calls POST /api/auth/refresh
       with the refresh_token cookie, gets a new access_token, and
       retries the original request once.

6. Logout
   └── Next.js API route clears cookies + calls POST /api/auth/logout
```

**Token storage:** Tokens are stored in httpOnly cookies set by a Next.js API route (`/api/auth/callback`). They are never accessible from JavaScript in the browser, preventing XSS theft.

**Server Component auth:** Server Components read the token from the cookie via `cookies()` from `next/headers` and pass it to `lib/api.ts` directly.
{% elif auth_method == "oauth2" %}
### OAuth2 Authentication (end-to-end)

The Symfony backend acts as an OAuth2 Authorization Server (using `league/oauth2-server`). The frontend uses the Authorization Code flow with PKCE.

```
1. User clicks "Log in"
   └── Frontend redirects to Symfony /oauth/authorize with code_challenge

2. User authenticates at Symfony
   └── Symfony redirects back to Next.js /api/auth/callback?code=...

3. Next.js exchanges the code
   └── POST /oauth/token  { code, code_verifier }
       Returns { access_token, refresh_token, expires_in }

4. Tokens stored in httpOnly cookies (Next.js API route)

5. Subsequent requests attach Authorization: Bearer <access_token>

6. Refresh is handled transparently by lib/api.ts
```
{% endif %}
{% endif %}

